---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import MadeByKaj from '../../components/MadeByKaj.astro';

const basePath = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const githubUrl = 'https://github.com/Found-in-Space/pipeline';
---

<Layout
	title="Build | Found in Space"
	description="Over a billion stars from ESA's Gaia mission and the Hipparcos survey, merged, spatially indexed, and navigable in a browser. The full open pipeline."
>
	<SiteHeader section="Build" />

	<main class="page">
		<section class="hero">
			<p class="eyebrow">Build</p>
			<h1>Over a billion stars. Each placed in three-dimensional space.</h1>
			<p class="intro">
				Not a simulation. Not a model. Real distance measurements from ESA's Gaia spacecraft,
				combined with data from the historic Hipparcos survey, processed into a single navigable
				dataset. Every step is open — the catalogues, the pipeline code, the spatial index, and
				the viewer.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="pipeline">
			<article class="panel panel--accent step">
				<p class="panel__eyebrow">Step one</p>
				<h2>Two surveys, one star map</h2>
				<p>
					Gaia DR3 measured over a billion stars with sub-milliarcsecond precision — positions,
					parallaxes, proper motions, colours. But Gaia's detectors saturate on the brightest
					stars: Sirius, Vega, Betelgeuse. These are exactly the stars people recognise.
				</p>
				<p>
					The Hipparcos mission (ESA, 1989–1993) was purpose-built for bright-star astrometry.
					Its 118,000 stars anchor the naked-eye sky that Gaia cannot reliably reach.
				</p>
				<p>
					About 100,000 stars appear in both catalogues. The pipeline produces exactly one
					canonical row per physical star — choosing the better measurement for each, handling
					binary systems, and manually curating the handful of cases that defeat automation
					entirely (including the Sun, which does not appear in either catalogue).
				</p>
				<a class="step__link" href={`${basePath}build/gaia-and-hipparcos-star-catalogues/`}>
					How the merge works →
				</a>
			</article>

			<article class="panel step">
				<p class="panel__eyebrow">Step two</p>
				<h2>Cleaned, corrected, and positioned</h2>
				<p>
					Each star gets a distance — from the catalog parallax where reliable, from
					Bailer-Jones probabilistic estimates where not, from photometric modelling where
					those fail, and from a conservative prior as a last resort. Each tier is flagged.
				</p>
				<p>
					Positions are propagated to a common epoch (J2016.0) using proper motions, and
					converted to Sun-centred Cartesian coordinates in parsecs. Temperature comes from
					spectroscopic measurements where available, falling back through colour cascades
					to a default.
				</p>
				<p>
					The result is a HEALPix-partitioned Parquet table: one row per star, a fixed schema,
					quality flags packed into each record.
				</p>
			</article>

			<article class="panel step">
				<p class="panel__eyebrow">Step three</p>
				<h2>Indexed for the browser</h2>
				<p>
					A browser cannot download a billion-row table. The merged data is encoded into a
					spatial octree — a tree structure that divides 3D space into nested cells across
					fourteen levels. Each star is placed into a level based on its brightness: the
					brightest stars sit in the shallowest, largest cells, while fainter stars go into
					progressively deeper, smaller ones. The threshold at each level is tuned to how
					the human eye perceives starlight.
				</p>
				<p>
					When you navigate the viewer, it loads cells level by level. Bright-star cells
					have large visibility radii and load from anywhere in the scene. Faint-star cells
					only load when you fly close enough that those stars would actually be visible.
					Everything else stays on the server until you need it.
				</p>
			</article>
		</section>

		<section class="links-section">
			<div class="links-section__intro">
				<p class="eyebrow">Technical notes</p>
				<h2>Read more about how it works.</h2>
			</div>
			<div class="links-section__cards">
				<a class="link-card" href={`${basePath}build/gaia-and-hipparcos-star-catalogues/`}>
					<h3>Gaia and Hipparcos — merging two star catalogues</h3>
					<p>
						Why two surveys are needed, how 100,000 duplicate stars are deduplicated,
						and how the pipeline handles cases that defeat automated matching.
					</p>
					<span class="link-card__cta">Read →</span>
				</a>
				<a class="link-card" href={`${basePath}build/download-the-star-data/`}>
					<h3>Download and run the pipeline yourself</h3>
					<p>
						The pipeline is open source. Start with a 16 MB sample of the brightest stars,
						or build the full dataset from scratch using the Gaia Archive.
					</p>
					<span class="link-card__cta">Read →</span>
				</a>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="open-source">
			<div class="panel panel--wide">
				<p class="panel__eyebrow">Open source</p>
				<h2>The pipeline is on GitHub</h2>
				<p>
					The data pipeline code — catalogues, astrometry, photometry, merging, and the
					project configuration format — is published under the MIT licence at
					<a href={githubUrl} rel="noopener noreferrer">github.com/Found-in-Space/pipeline</a>.
					Requires Python ≥ 3.13 and <code>uv</code>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<MadeByKaj />
	</main>
</Layout>

<style>
	.hero {
		padding: 4.2rem 0 2.8rem;
		max-width: 52rem;
	}

	h1 {
		margin: 0;
		font-size: clamp(2.6rem, 6vw, 4.4rem);
		font-weight: 600;
		line-height: 0.97;
		letter-spacing: -0.03em;
	}

	h2 {
		margin: 0 0 1rem;
		font-size: 1.55rem;
		font-weight: 600;
		line-height: 1.1;
		letter-spacing: -0.02em;
		color: var(--fis-text);
	}

	h3 {
		margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
		font-size: 1.25rem;
		font-weight: 600;
		line-height: 1.2;
		color: var(--fis-text);
	}

	.intro {
		max-width: 46rem;
		margin: 1.5rem 0 0;
		font-size: 1.18rem;
		line-height: 1.75;
		color: var(--fis-text-soft);
	}

	/* Pipeline steps */

	.pipeline {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
		gap: 1rem;
		margin-bottom: 4rem;
	}

	.step {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
	}

	.step p {
		margin: 0 0 1rem;
		font-size: 1rem;
		line-height: 1.75;
		color: var(--fis-text-soft);
	}

	.step__link {
		margin-top: auto;
		padding-top: 1.25rem;
		font-size: 0.95rem;
		color: var(--fis-gold);
		text-decoration-color: rgba(242, 200, 121, 0.35);
	}

	/* Links section */

	.links-section {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr;
		gap: 3rem;
		padding: 4rem 0;
		border-top: 1px solid var(--fis-line);
		margin-bottom: 1rem;
	}

	.links-section__intro h2 {
		margin: 0;
		font-size: 2rem;
		line-height: 1.05;
		max-width: 12ch;
	}

	.links-section__cards {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 1rem;
	}

	.link-card {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		padding: 1.5rem;
		background: var(--fis-panel);
		border: 1px solid var(--fis-line);
		border-radius: var(--fis-radius);
		backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
		text-decoration: none;
		transition:
			border-color 160ms ease,
			transform 160ms ease;
	}

	.link-card:hover {
		border-color: rgba(242, 200, 121, 0.3);
		transform: translateX(6px);
	}

	.link-card p {
		margin: 0 0 1rem;
		font-size: 1rem;
		line-height: 1.65;
		color: var(--fis-text-soft);
	}

	.link-card__cta {
		font-size: 0.9rem;
		color: var(--fis-gold);
	}

	/* Open source panel */

	.open-source {
		margin-bottom: 4rem;
	}

	.open-source h2 {
		font-size: 1.4rem;
	}

	.open-source p {
		margin: 0;
		line-height: 1.75;
		color: var(--fis-text-soft);
	}

	.open-source a {
		color: var(--fis-gold);
		text-decoration-color: rgba(242, 200, 121, 0.4);
	}

	.open-source code {
		font-size: 0.9em;
		color: var(--fis-blue);
	}

	@media (max-width: 960px) {
		.pipeline {
			grid-template-columns: 1fr;
		}

		.links-section {
			grid-template-columns: 1fr;
			gap: 2rem;
		}
	}
</style>
